'https://twitter.com/intent/tweet?text=https://www.facebook.com/ForestAnimalRescue/photos/a.697939026903667/3660710107293196/?type=3+Update on rehab bear cub, Gabby.\nGabby is doing well, she has started finishing her entire diet and is foraging on the scatter mix we throw into her enclosure. Foraging is really important, it’s a natural behavior that gets her to start eating and looking for food on her own, which will give her a better survival rate in the wild. Her forage consists of leaves, nuts, acorns and palmetto berries, things she will all eat in the wild. Our goal is to get her to gain as much weight as possible, she is very underweight for a cub her age, especially for the season. She has also been seen jumping and swimming in her pool as you can see. She still has a healthy dose of fear for humans - and we want to keep it that way! The best thing for her is to not associate humans with food or care (that is why we are hands off and Gabby is not able to see us) because we don’t want a habituated bear going to humans for food in the wild - and neither should you, so never feed any wild animal!#animalsanctuary #accreditedsanctuary #truesanctuary #sanctuary #animalrescue #rescue #forestanimalrescue #florida #rehab #rehabilitation #wildliferehab #rehabandrelease #rescueandrelease #blackbear #americanblackbear #bears #bear #wildlife #animals', "https://twitter.com/intent/tweet?text=https://twitter.com/ForestAnimalRes/status/1220533373912915968+Even if you snoozed, you don't need to lose!
